<p class="written-japanese">ã©ã“ã€€ã§ã€€___ ã‚’ã€€ãŸã¹ã¾ã™ã€€ã‹ï¼Ÿ</p>
<p>In this sentence, <strong>â€œdokoâ€</strong> means "where", and <strong>â€œtaberuâ€</strong> means "eat", but we use <strong>â€œtabemasuâ€</strong> as that is more formal.</p>
<p>My reply to that would be:</p>
<p class="english">I order ____ and eat it at home</p>
<p class="english-romaji">Watashi wa ___ wo chumon shite ie de tabemasu.</p>
<p class="written-japanese">ã‚ãŸã—ã€€ã‚ã€€___ ã‚’ã€€æ³¨æ–‡ã€€ã—ã¦ã€€å®¶ã€€ã§ã€€ãŸã¹ã¾ã™</p>
<p>Here, <strong>â€œchumon/tyumonâ€</strong> means "order", and <strong>â€œshiteâ€</strong> means "do", <strong>â€œieâ€</strong> means "home/house" and <strong>â€œdeâ€</strong>, as discussed above, means "at" - So the direct translation is a bit confusing - I sushi order do home at eat - But in Japanese, this makes sense!</p>
<p>If you want to say you eat at a restaurant, you can just say</p>
<p class="english-romaji">Restaurant o mise</p>
<p class="written-japanese">ãƒ¬ã‚¹ãƒˆãƒ©ãƒ³ã€€ãŠ åº—</p>
<p>Where <strong>â€œResturantâ€</strong> means "restaurant" (obviously!) and <strong>â€œo miseâ€</strong> means "shop"</p>

<h2>Manners</h2>
<p>When youâ€™re at a restaurant, and you want the attention of the staff, you can just askâ€¦</p>
