<p><strong>â€œNigriâ€</strong> here means "grab" - Iâ€™m not too sure why itâ€™s called grab sushi, perhaps itâ€™s because of the small grabbable size of the sushi?</p>
<p class="english">(hand)roll sushi</p>
<p class="english-romaji">(te)maki sushi</p>
<p>This one makes a lot more sense! <strong>â€œTeâ€</strong> means "hand", <strong>â€œmakiâ€</strong> means "roll" - This means sushi which is made and rolled by hand!</p>
<p>Some additional food words are <strong>â€œNoriâ€</strong> which means "seaweed", <strong>â€œOnigiriâ€</strong> which means "rice ball" and <strong>â€œOmisoshiruâ€</strong>, which, if we break it down â€œOâ€ means respect but hasn't got a direct translation <strong>â€œmisoâ€</strong> is "soy-paste", and <strong>â€œshiruâ€</strong> means "soup"!</p>

<h2>Meals</h2>
<p>In English, we have breakfast, lunch and dinner, but these arenâ€™t really directly translated into Japanese! Instead in Japan, the word <strong>â€œGohanâ€</strong> which means "meal", is used in addition to the time of the day to indicate the three different meals of the day.</p>
<p class="english">Morning meal</p>
<p class="english-romaji">Asa-gohan</p>
<p class="english">Noon meal</p>
<p class="english-romaji">Hiru-gohan</p>
<p class="english">Night meal</p>
<p class="english-romaji">Yoru-gohan</p>
<p>From this, you can see <strong>â€œAsaâ€</strong> means "morning", <strong>â€œHiruâ€</strong> means "noon", and <strong>â€œYoruâ€</strong> means "night"!</p>

